{%- comment -%}
  SBJ / SKIMS-match HEADER CSS — the SINGLE owner of the transparent home-page header
  skin. Loaded last in <body> from layout/theme.liquid so it wins source order; the
  theme editor can never revert it.

  ── REBUILT 2026-06-24 (disappear-on-scroll fix) ──
  The previous version forced the white/transparent look with a JS scroll hack
  (`html.sbj-hdr-top`, added at scrollY<=4) that ALSO force-wrote `data-sticky-state`
  and `data-scroll-direction` on the native element — racing Horizon's
  IntersectionObserver — and zeroed `--closed-underlay-height` (the solid background).
  Because the white text + background-removal were keyed on scroll POSITION, not on the
  real sticky state, scrolling back to the top forced white text onto a white/no
  background → "the header disappears." The race also made it flicker.

  THIS REBUILD: ZERO JavaScript. We never write datasets and never touch
  `--closed-underlay-height`. Horizon's native sticky+transparent mechanism is left
  fully intact (in `sticky="always"` mode it is permanently `position:sticky; top:-1px`
  and NEVER translates or hides — the bar is always physically present). We ONLY
  re-color, and every rule is gated on:

      #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active'])

  i.e. it applies ONLY while the header is genuinely transparent over the hero. The
  instant the header sticks (`data-sticky-state='active'`), every selector below stops
  matching and Horizon renders its native solid header (white bg / #2d2a26 text / 1px
  border / nav-row logo). White text therefore can NEVER reach the solid scrolled bar,
  so it can never land on white. `:not(...='active')` (rather than `='inactive'`) also
  matches the pre-observer first paint, so there is no solid-then-transparent flash.

  Desktop only (>=750px). Mobile uses Horizon's native nav-row logo + scheme unchanged.
  Structural rules (logo position/size, icon footprints, column padding, .header-logo
  hide, nav-row logo reveal on scroll, announcement layout) stay in
  sections/header-announcements.liquid.
{%- endcomment -%}
<style>
/* ============================================================
   TRANSPARENT OVERLAY PERSISTENCE — the real "header disappears /
   white band when I scroll up and down" fix.

   Horizon makes the transparent header overlay the hero by pulling the
   FIRST homepage section UP under the header (negative margin-top =
   -header-height). On this store the first section is the empty `sbj_css`
   CSS-holder section, and Horizon's pull-up on it is LOST after you scroll
   down and back up — the hero then drops BELOW the header, exposing a white
   page band where the white nav text becomes invisible (only hover, which
   fills the bar white + darkens text, made it reappear).

   We force the pull-up persistently so the hero ALWAYS sits behind the
   header — fresh load AND after any scroll cycle. Homepage only (the
   [transparent] attribute exists only there); all viewports, to match
   Horizon's native (non-media-gated) overlay. Verified: heroTop + "hero
   behind nav" stay identical before and after scrolling.
   ============================================================ */
  body:has(#header-component[transparent]) main > .shopify-section:first-child {
    margin-top: calc(var(--header-height) * -1) !important;
  }

@media screen and (min-width: 750px) {
  /* ============================================================
     TRANSPARENT OVER HERO  —  home, header not yet stuck
     ============================================================ */

  /* Nav links + right-column action links/buttons: WHITE + soft white halo */
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) :is(
    .menu-list__link,
    .menu-list__link-title,
    .header__column--right a,
    .header__column--right button
  ) {
    color: #ffffff !important;
    text-shadow: 0 0 4px rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6), 0 1px 2px rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);
  }

  /* Right-side icons: white + white drop-shadow */
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) :is(
    .header-actions svg,
    .header__column--right svg,
    .menu-list__link svg
  ) {
    color: #ffffff !important;
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 3px rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.7));
  }

  /* No divider line under the header rows while transparent */
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) :is(
    .header__row--top,
    .header__row--top .header__columns
  ) {
    border-bottom: 0 !important;
  }

  /* ---- Announcement row over the hero (a sibling section) ----
     Keyed on the header's transparent state via :has() on <body>. */
  body:has(#header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active'])) .announcement-bar :is(
    p,
    .announcement-bar__text,
    .announcement-bar__logo-text
  ) {
    color: #2d2a26 !important;            /* dark announcement text over the hero */
  }
  body:has(#header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active'])) .announcement-bar {
    --border-bottom-width: 0px;           /* no divider under the announcement */
  }
  /* The SBJ logo PNG has a white background → multiply drops the box, leaving the dark
     mark crisp over the bright hero. On scroll the native nav-row logo takes over. */
  body:has(#header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active'])) .announcement-bar__logo img {
    filter: none;
    mix-blend-mode: multiply;
  }
  body:has(#header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active'])) .announcement-bar__logo {
    display: inline-flex !important;      /* keep the logo visible at the top */
  }

  /* ============================================================
     HOVER over the transparent header → fill solid white, dark text
     (previews the scrolled look). Smooth background fade; NO instant
     !important height flip across a scroll threshold (that strobed).
     ============================================================ */
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) {
    transition: background-color 0.15s ease;
  }
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']):hover,
  body:has(.announcement-bar:hover) #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) {
    background-color: #ffffff !important;
  }
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']):hover :is(
    .menu-list__link, .menu-list__link-title, .header__column--right a, .header__column--right button
  ),
  body:has(.announcement-bar:hover) #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) :is(
    .menu-list__link, .menu-list__link-title, .header__column--right a, .header__column--right button
  ) {
    color: #2d2a26 !important;
    text-shadow: none !important;
  }
  #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']):hover .header__column--right svg,
  body:has(.announcement-bar:hover) #header-component[transparent]:not([data-sticky-state='active']) .header__column--right svg {
    color: #2d2a26 !important;
    filter: none !important;
  }

  /* ============================================================
     SCROLLED / SOLID STATE  →  no rules needed. Once
     data-sticky-state='active' none of the above match and Horizon
     renders its native solid header. White is never emitted there.
     ============================================================ */
}
</style>
